    "content": [
        {
            "id": "block-001",
            "tag": "h1",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "Time"
        },
        {
            "id": "block-002",
            "tag": "p",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "`Time` lets you read the game's clock. You'll use it for timers, cooldowns, animations, and — most importantly — to make movement run at the same speed on every device, whether it's a fast gaming PC or a slow phone."
        },
        {
            "id": "block-003",
            "tag": "h2",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "The three clocks"
        },
        {
            "id": "block-004",
            "tag": "table",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "headers": [
                "Method",
                "What it gives you"
            ],
            "rows": [
                [
                    "`GameTime()`",
                    "How many seconds the **game** has been running. This is the clock to use for gameplay timers."
                ],
                [
                    "`RealTime()`",
                    "Real-world seconds, measured independently of the game."
                ],
                [
                    "`DeltaTime()`",
                    "How many seconds passed since the **last frame** — a tiny number used to keep movement smooth and consistent (explained below)."
                ]
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "block-005",
            "tag": "h2",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "Why DeltaTime matters"
        },
        {
            "id": "block-006",
            "tag": "p",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "Your game updates many times per second, frame by frame. A fast device draws more frames than a slow one. If you move an object \"a little bit every frame\", it would travel **faster on fast devices** — which is unfair and unpredictable."
        },
        {
            "id": "block-007",
            "tag": "p",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "`DeltaTime()` fixes this. By multiplying your speed by it, you turn \"per frame\" into \"per second\", so the result is identical everywhere:"
        },
        {
            "id": "block-008",
            "tag": "code",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "lines": [
                "// 5 units PER SECOND — correct on every device.",
                "float distance = 5.0 * Time.DeltaTime();",
                "",
                "// A countdown that ticks down in real seconds.",
                "timeLeft = timeLeft - Time.DeltaTime();",
                "if (timeLeft <= 0.0)",
                "{",
                "    Debug.Log(\"Time's up!\");",
                "}"
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "block-009",
            "tag": "important",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "Rule of thumb: whenever you change something **a bit each frame** (movement, rotation, a fading value, a timer), multiply by `Time.DeltaTime()`. Without it, your game behaves differently on different hardware."
        },
        {
            "id": "block-010",
            "tag": "note",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "These are all **methods**, so always include the parentheses: write `Time.DeltaTime()`, not `Time.DeltaTime`."
        },
        {
            "id": "block-011",
            "tag": "h2",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "Building a cooldown"
        },
        {
            "id": "block-012",
            "tag": "p",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "A common pattern: remember *when* something happened with `GameTime()`, then check if enough time has passed before allowing it again."
        },
        {
            "id": "block-013",
            "tag": "code",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "lines": [
                "float lastShotTime = -999.0;",
                "",
                "void Fire()",
                "{",
                "    // Only allow firing every 0.5 seconds.",
                "    if (Time.GameTime() - lastShotTime >= 0.5)",
                "    {",
                "        lastShotTime = Time.GameTime();",
                "        // ...spawn the bullet...",
                "    }",
                "}"
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "block-014",
            "tag": "h2",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "Full method reference"
        },
        {
            "id": "block-015",
